\title{Catcolab Petri Nets}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{CatColab Petri Nets - concurrent system modeling via places (states), transitions (events), and token flow. Foundation for process algebra, workflow, and chemical reaction networks.}

\subtree{
\title{CatColab Petri Nets: Concurrent Systems}
\p{\strong{Trit}: +1 (PLUS - generator) \strong{Color}: Magenta (#FF00FF)}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Petri nets in CatColab model concurrent and distributed systems:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Places}: States holding tokens (resources, conditions)}
\li{\strong{Transitions}: Events that fire when enabled}
\li{\strong{Arcs}: Flow of tokens between places and transitions}
\li{\strong{Tokens}: Resources consumed/produced by transitions}
}

\p{Petri nets are the categorical foundation for process algebra, workflow modeling, and chemical reaction networks.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Mathematical Foundation}
\p{A Petri net is a bipartite graph:}

\pre{\startverb
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    PETRI NET                         │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Places (States):                                    │
│    (P1) Ready   (P2) Running   (P3) Done            │
│                                                      │
│  Transitions (Events):                               │
│    [T1] Start   [T2] Finish                          │
│                                                      │
│  Arcs (Token Flow):                                  │
│    P1 → T1 → P2 → T2 → P3                           │
│                                                      │
│  Diagram:                                            │
│    (P1)●──►[T1]──►(P2)──►[T2]──►(P3)                │
│     ●=token                                          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Free Symmetric Monoidal Category}
\p{Petri nets are the \strong{free symmetric monoidal category} on a signature:}

\pre{\startverb
Objects: P₁, P₂, ..., Pₙ (places)
Morphisms: Generated by transitions

Tensor: P₁ ⊗ P₂ (concurrent resources)
Composition: Sequential firing

Example:
  T: P₁ ⊗ P₂ → P₃ ⊗ P₄
  "Transition T consumes tokens from P₁, P₂
   and produces tokens in P₃, P₄"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Double Theory}
\pre{\startverb
// Petri net double theory
pub fn th_petri_net() -> DiscreteDblTheory {
    let mut cat = FpCategory::new();

    // Object type
    cat.add_ob_generator(name("Place"));

    // Morphism type (transitions as structured morphisms)
    cat.add_mor_generator(name("Transition"), name("Place"), name("Place"));

    // Monoidal structure (parallel composition)
    // P ⊗ Q represents "P and Q concurrently"

    cat.into()
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{CatColab Implementation}
\subtree{
\title{Place Declaration}
\pre{\startverb
{
  "type": "ObDecl",
  "name": "Idle",
  "theory_type": "Place",
  "description": "process waiting for input"
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Transition Declaration}
\pre{\startverb
{
  "type": "MorDecl",
  "name": "activate",
  "inputs": ["Idle", "Resource"],
  "outputs": ["Active"],
  "theory_type": "Transition",
  "description": "process starts when resource available"
}
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Practical Examples}
\subtree{
\title{Example 1: Producer-Consumer}
\pre{\startverb
Places: Buffer (capacity N), Produced, Consumed

Transitions:
  produce: Empty → Buffer + Produced
  consume: Buffer → Consumed

Tokens: Buffer starts empty, count items produced/consumed
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example 2: Dining Philosophers}
\pre{\startverb
Places: Thinking(i), Eating(i), Fork(i) for i=1..5

Transitions:
  pickup(i): Thinking(i) ⊗ Fork(i) ⊗ Fork(i+1) → Eating(i)
  putdown(i): Eating(i) → Thinking(i) ⊗ Fork(i) ⊗ Fork(i+1)

Deadlock possible when all pick up left fork simultaneously
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example 3: Chemical Reaction (A + B → C)}
\pre{\startverb
Places: A, B, C (species concentrations as token counts)

Transitions:
  react: A ⊗ B → C

Stochastic: Rate = k·[A]·[B] (mass action)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Connection to Stock-Flow}
\p{Petri nets and stock-flow diagrams are \strong{equivalent}:}

\pre{\startverb
Petri Net           ≅   Stock-Flow
  Place             ↔   Stock
  Transition        ↔   Flow
  Token count       ↔   Population
  Firing rate       ↔   Mass-action rate
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{AlgebraicPetri.jl Integration}
\pre{\startverb
using AlgebraicPetri
using Catlab

# Define SIR as Petri net
sir_petri = @acset LabelledPetriNet begin
  S = 3  # places: S, I, R
  T = 2  # transitions: infect, recover

  tname = [:infect, :recover]
  sname = [:S, :I, :R]

  is = [1, 2]     # infect inputs: S, I
  os = [2, 2]     # infect outputs: I, I
  it = [1, 1]     # transition indices
  ot = [1, 1]
end

# Compose Petri nets
combined = sir_petri ⊕ vaccination_petri
\stopverb}
}

